{"title_page": "List of Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. records and statistics", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n[[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers Football Club]] is an English [[Association football|football]] club based in [[Wolverhampton]]. The club was founded as St Luke's in 1877, soon becoming Wolverhampton Wanderers, before being a founder member of [[the Football League]] in 1888.<ref name=\"Record\">{{cite book |author=Matthews, Tony |title=Wolverhampton Wanderers: The Complete Record |year=2008 |publisher=Breedon Books |location=Derby |isbn=978-1-85983-632-3}}</ref> Since that time, the club has played in all four professional divisions of the [[English football league system|English football pyramid]], and been champions of all these levels.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/news/theknowledge/0,9204,534448,00.html |title=Wolves: The only team to have won it all |publisher=The Guardian|date=9 August 2001}}</ref> They have also been involved in European football, having been one of the first English clubs to enter the [[UEFA Champions League|European Cup]], as well as reaching the final of the first staging of the [[UEFA Cup]].<ref name=\"Database\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fchd.info/WOLVERHW.HTM |title=Wolverhampton Wanderers |publisher=Football Club History Database}}</ref>\n\nThis list encompasses all honours won by Wolverhampton Wanderers and records set by the club, their managers and their players. The player records section includes details of the club's leading goalscorers and those who have made most appearances in first-team competitions, as well as transfer fee records paid and received by the club. A list of streaks recording all elements of the game (wins, losses, clean sheets, etc.) is also presented.\n\n==Honours==\nIn the all-time top flight league table since the league's inception in 1888, Wolves sit in the top fifteen, in terms of all-time English first level league position.<ref name=\"RSSSF\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engalltime.html |title= a) England \u2014 First Level All-Time Tables |publisher=-\u2014-\u2014}}{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engprof-alltime.html |title= b) England \u2014 Professional Football All-Time Tables |publisher=RSSSF}}</ref>\n\nAlternatively, they sit in the top four, behind only [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] and [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in terms of all-time league position from points gained at any level of English professional football.<ref name=\"RSSSF\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engalltime.html |title= a) England \u2014 First Level All-Time Tables |publisher=-\u2014-\u2014}}{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engprof-alltime.html |title= b) England \u2014 Professional Football All-Time Tables |publisher=RSSSF}}</ref>\n\nCumulatively, they are the joint 11th most successful club in domestic English football history, tied with [[Nottingham Forest F.C. |Nottingham Forest]]. One place behind [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], with nine major trophy wins, not including super cups. Alternatively they are joint 10th with Nottingham Forrest, in competitive honours with 13 trophy wins, behind [[Newcastle United F.C. |Newcastle United]].(see [[List of football clubs in England by competitive honours won|here]]).\n\nUniquely, they are the only club to have won titles in five different Football League divisions,<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> and, in 1988, became the first team to have been champions of all four professional leagues in English football; although this feat has since been matched by [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] (in 1992) and [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston]] (in 1996). They remain the only club to have won all the main domestic cup competitions ([[FA Cup]], [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] and [[Football League Trophy]]) currently contested in English football.<ref>\"Wolves completed the set when they won the (then) Sherpa Van Trophy in 1988. Apart from four FA Cups (1893, 1908, 1949, 1960), three First Division championships (1953\u201354, 1957\u201358, 1958\u201359) and two League Cups (1974, 1980), the Wolves set also includes the Charity Shield (beating Forest in 1959), the FA Youth Cup (1958) and the Anglo-Scottish Cup (1971). Having also won the Second Division (1931\u201332, 1976\u201377), the Third Division (1988\u201389), the Third Division North (1923\u201324) and the Fourth Division (1987\u201388)\", only the renamed Championship remained and was duly completed (2008\u201309). Bryant, Tom; Roopanarine, Les; Chesterton, George; [https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/oct/03/theknowledge \"KNOWLEDGE ARCHIVE\"] ''[[The Guardian|Guardian.co.uk]]'', 3 October 2007</ref>\n\n===League===\n'''[[List of English football champions|First Division/Premier League]]'''\n*Champions: [[1953\u201354 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1953\u201354]], [[1957\u201358 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1957\u201358]], [[1958\u201359 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1958\u201359]]\n*Runners-up: [[1937\u201338 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1937\u201338]], [[1938\u201339 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1938\u201339]], [[1949\u201350 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1949\u201350]], [[1954\u201355 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1954\u201355]], [[1959\u201360 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1959-60]]\n\n'''[[List of teams promoted from the English Football League Championship and predecessors|Second Division/Championship]]'''\n*Champions: [[1931\u201332 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1931\u201332]], [[1976\u201377 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1976\u201377]], [[2008\u201309 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2008\u201309]], [[2017\u201318 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2017\u201318]]\n*Runners-up: [[1966\u201367 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1966\u201367]], [[1982\u201383 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|1982\u